Deal with quality value equals to zero.

According to the specification:

HTTP content negotiation (section 12) uses short "floating point" numbers to indicate the relative importance ("weight") of various negotiable parameters. A weight is normalized to a real number in the range 0 through 1, where 0 is the minimum and 1 the maximum value. If a parameter has a quality value of 0, then content with this parameter is `not acceptable' for the client. HTTP/1.1 applications MUST NOT generate more than three digits after the decimal point. User configuration of these values SHOULD also be limited in this fashion.

  qvalue         = ( "0" [ "." 0*3DIGIT ] )
                 | ( "1" [ "." 0*3("0") ] )

"Quality values" is a misnomer, since these values merely represent relative degradation in desired quality.

http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec3.html#sec3.9

Merge pull request #180 from fnando/ios-webview

Detect iOS apps webview. Close #179.

Detect iOS apps webview. Close #179.

The user agent from an app webview doesn't include the `Safari/:version` part. We can possibly detect if request is coming from an app's webview if it doesn't include this string.

There's one implication: iOS webviews or Safari Web Apps aren't detected as Safari, because they don't include the `Safari` string.

Merge pull request #168 from fnando/microsoft-compatibility-view

Detect IE/Edge versions based on compatibility view.

Detect IE/Edge versions based on compatibility view.

The big change here is that Browser#version and Browser#full_version will always return the real browser version. If you want the compatibility view version, you can get it with Browser#msie_version and Browser#msie_full_version.

Another change is that IE/Edge are considered modern browsers only when not runnnig in compatibility view mode. If you need to change this behavior, create your own Browser.modern_rules.

Closes #51.

Add Browser#known? method

This method returns true if the browser has successfully been detected i.e.
it has been possible to determine which browser the User-Agent string belongs
to (Chrome, Firefox, etc). If the browser has not been detected then this
method will return false.

Expand list of bots

At Causes, we have been running a user agent string check for bots with
a list I curated from our server logs. This commit adds some bots from
our list to the bots in this gem to provide a more complete and accurate
view of who is a bot.

Convert double quotes to single quotes in bots

Since we don't need string interpolation here, and we aren't using any
single quotes in these strings that would require escaping, we may as
well use single quotes everywhere.

At the same time, I added a trailing comma to the end of the hash.
